node.text:
Practiced a whole bunch of styles on my mannequin today! I hope this inspires you to not only practice when you get a chance but to actually have fun doing so. ❤️🤗🎉
⠀
You don’t have to do things the same exact way I did or the same exact way another person does. Enjoy freely wondering, exploring, experimenting, discovering, and learning. This is your craft, your love, your passion. ❤️❤️❤️
⠀
Curling with my cordless @dysonprohair @dysonprohair Corrale™ Straightener allowed me to effortlessly get into many different positions while styling. The flexing plates hugged each section of hair preventing it from slipping out. This allowed me to curl with less passes and less heat. ❤️
⠀
If you’d like to rewatch it later on, here’s the list of styles I tried and at what time in the video it plays:
⠀
0:05 - Twist once and pull (away from the face)
0:45 - Twist once and pull (alternate directions)
1:36 - Twist twice and pull
2:20 - Twist, pull, and smooth
2:53 - Curl all the same direction and set
4:42 - Wave up and down horizontally
⠀
Love you guys!! ❤️❤️❤️
⠀
@modernsalon @dysonhair @dysonhairpro #modernsalonxdyson #modernsalon #dysonhairpro #dysonhair
⠀

node.text:
Volume Up! 🔊
⠀
Side Part Layering Series (Part 3)
⠀
Sometimes, I get clients with deep side parts who want their layers to be even on both sides. ✂️
⠀
I try to explain to them that they’ll either be too skinny on the lighter side of the part or too thick on the heavier side of the part. Their layers will be even, but their silhouette won’t.
⠀
Their worry is that the top layers on both sides will end up looking visibly uneven. I explain to them that if the hair is cut well, the layers should seamlessly blend. They should not see 1, 2 or 3 layers that some of our clients ask for (have you had those clients?). My clients have always ended up choosing to look visually even instead of technically even.
⠀
There’s no right or wrong for me. To me, it’s all about what the client wants …but I still explain to them the reality of what they are asking for and give them alternatives during consultation. I let them know that I’m on their side and I want to make their hair dreams come true. ❤️❤️❤️
⠀
This video isn’t a tutorial on how to do the haircut. This isn’t even how I do it. There are many many ways to do it though. This just visually explains the concept of why cutting even layers on a side part creates an uneven silhouette. ✂️
⠀
What if your client insists on having even layers and also wants to look visually even? What if you don’t want to rely on point cutting the heck out of it? That’s what I have plannned for the final video of this series. Let me know if you are interested. Love you guys!!! ❤️❤️❤️

- Section size
- Curling direction
- How each section is formed while being heated
⠀
2. Dress & Detail
- Brush all the curls out with a boar bristled brush
- lightly comb upwards underneath each ridge to accentuate it
- Make baby hairs lay by lightly misting hairspray from afar and by using the bottle to shape them into the waves.
⠀
⠀
Using my Corrale ™ made it easy for me to create uniform curls. Because it was cordless, I was able to hold it in the same position and just keep twisting until all the hair wrapped into a curl. Because of the flexing plates, it held the hair in the same position. The hair didn’t spread out or slip out of the straightener. This which allowed me to avoid having to keep having to go through hair that has already been heated just to style ones that were missed.
⠀

Triangular Layers ❤️
⠀
BACK:
I took a vertical section in the center. I pulled the hair up because I wanted it to be shorter on top and longer on the bottom. I dropped hair below the occipital bone because I wanted to keep the perimeter thick enough.
⠀
I cut a line connecting my desired length for the shortest layer to the hair I lifted from the bottom. My finger angle just happened to be straight across to make that happen.
⠀
I worked my way to the right, making each new section travel to the previous section, using it as a guide for cutting. This made each section longer than the previous.
⠀
Once I reached the part of the head where it starts to round into the sides, I used a stationary guide. All sections after that traveled to the same guide. This made each new section get longer quicker.
⠀
I did the same thing on the left side.
⠀
⠀
FRONT:
My plan was for the hair to be shorter in the back and longer in the front. I took a guide from the back and tried to angle my finger to keep the front long enough. I couldn’t make it  long enough so I pulled that section back to make the hair in the front travel more.
⠀
I took new sections working my way to one side of the head, making each section travel to the previous section using it as a guide. Once I reach the parietal ridge, I used a stationary guide. This made the hair shorter on top and longer on the bottom.
⠀
I did the same thing on the other side.
⠀
⠀

If you’re a visual learner like me, I’d love love loooove to nerd-out with you in my in-person or live virtual classes! ❤️🤗✂️🎉
⠀
I graduated not knowing how to cut hair. I relied on memorizing haircuts, terms, angles etc from demos, hands-on classes, hair shows, videos etc. I was always worried that someone would sit in my chair and ask me for a haircut that I haven’t memorized. 😓
⠀
Things changed for me when I started understanding theory. ❤️ That’s what we’ll do at the class! 🤗
⠀
You’ll see lots and lots of visuals. I don’t want to just “tell” you things and you take my word for it. I want you to “see” it for yourself so you can get your own “aha” moments. 👀💡🤗🎉
⠀
I don’t want you to use leave with data/information. I want you to leave with knowledge. I want to show you how and encourage you to continue to be an independent thinker and learner. Why? Because I believe in you, your purpose, and the different you can make in the world by doing what you love. ❤️❤️❤️
⠀
Hope to see you at one of the classes! Click on the link on my bio for tickets and more information. ❤️❤️❤️

node.text:
Remember the thick curtain fringe we did last week? Here’s how to lighten it up while keeping the length: ❤️😊✂️
⠀
1. Determine how short you’d like the top to be
2. Find the length of the fringe below
3. Connect the lengths at an elevation where it’s easiest to connect them.
4. That first section will be your guide for the rest of the haircut
5. Pull the hair as far as needed to make sure you don’t cut off the length of the sides. ❤️❤️❤️
⠀
⠀
Layer more or layers less, change up the lengths, point cut, use a different tool etc. This is what I love about haircutting! ❤️ Hope you found this helpful and that it inspires you to have fun dreaming up ways to customize things for your clients. Have a wonderful day! Love you guys!! ❤️❤️❤️

node.text:
How to create a curtain fringe for fine hair. ❤️😊✂️
⠀
1. Determine how long you’d like the sides to be. Cut straight across and make sure that they’re even before proceeding.
⠀
2. Determine how short you’d like the middle to be. Cut a guide.
⠀
3. Cut a line connecting the middle to the sides. ❤️❤️❤️
⠀
⠀
Horizontally, it is shorter in the middle and longer towards the side. Vertically, it all falls the the same length, making that section of hair the thickest it could be. If you’d like it to be thicker, you could adjust the section size to add more hair into the fringe area. ✂️😊❤️
⠀
Hope you find this helpful! ❤️ If you know someone that might find this helpful too, I’d really really really appreciate it if you tag them in this post. Love you guys!!! ❤️❤️❤️

node.text:
Part 2! 🎉 Here’s how I cut the back of last week’s post. ❤️😊✂️
⠀
1. Drop some hair. The amount depends on how thick you’d like the perimeter to be.
⠀
2. Get a guide from the front.
⠀
3. Get a hair from the bottom of the section we’ll be layering.
⠀
4. Find the easiest elevation to connect those two lengths
⠀
5. Angle your finger as need to connect the two lengths.
⠀
6. Use that first section as a guide for the rest of the sections. ❤️
⠀
⠀
I posted how to do the front last week. ❤️ Hope you find this helpful! ❤️ If you know someone that might find this helpful too, I’d really really really appreciate it if you tag them in this post. Love you guys!!! ❤️❤️❤️

node.text:
Some people asked me how my last post would look on long hair. 🎉✂️ Here’s how to created a fringe that blends into layers on longer hair. ❤️
⠀
1. How long you’d like the front to be?
2. How long would you like the layers above the ears to be?
3. Elevate and connect the lengths where it is easiest to.
4. Angle your fingers as needed to connect them.
5. Use that first section as a guide for the rest of the sections. ❤️
⠀
Change the lengths that you’ll be connecting, change the overall length, use a traveling guide, stationary guide or a combination. ✂️ Detail the fringe more, point cut, use texturizing shears etc. ✂️ This is what I find super fun about cutting hair! ❤️😊🎉
⠀
I hope this inspires you to dream up different ways to customize this haircut, create completely different haircuts, and most of all have fun while doing it! ❤️💡✂️🤗🎉Love you guys!! ❤️❤️❤️
⠀
P.S.
I’ll share how to do the back on my next post! ❤️😊❤️

node.text:
How to create a curtain fringe that blends into layers on a bob ✂️❤️
⠀
1. Cut the length
⠀
2. Determine how long you’d like the fringe to be. Go a little bit longer to play it safe and to leave room for detailing later.
⠀
3. Determine how long you’d like the layers above the ears to be?
⠀
4. Elevate the hair and connect the lengths.
⠀
5. Angle your fingers as necessary to connect them.
⠀
6. Use that first section as a guide for the rest of the sections. ❤️
⠀
Change the length of the fringe, the rest of the layers or the overall length. ✂️ Detail the fringe, point cut, use texturizing shears etc. ✂️ That’s what I love about haircutting! ❤️🤗🎉
⠀
Hope this helps you dream up different ways to customize this haircut for your client, create new haircuts, and have fun in the process. Love you guys!! ❤️❤️❤️
⠀
Oh, I’ll be posting Part 2 (The back) next! 😊

Part 2! 🎉 Here’s how to layer the back of the shaggy bob we did last week. ❤️😊✂️
⠀
1. Drop some hair depending on how solid you’d like the perimeter to be.
2. Get a guide from what we’ve cut in the front
3. Find the bottom length of the hair you have in your hands
4. Find the elevation that will make it easiest for you to connect the two lengths
5. Angle your fingers as needed to connect them
6. Use that first section as a guide for the rest of the sections.
